children.subject: This is quite literally all you need for interview prep.
+1 to Elements of Programming Interviews. I think CTCI is good when you're first starting out but EPI takes it to the next level
Agree with anon above - if you want little more challenging questions than CTCI, I liked Elements of Programming Interviews

history.content:
Agreed with the follow-ups from below. CTCI and Leetcode enough for most interviews (barring perhaps some more quantitative ones).

Also, make sure that you know how to communicate your thoughts well while interviewing. I never practiced with friends (though I hear this can be very beneficial to do), but I found I was much much better (and less nervous) after many interviews. You might find it helpful to talk out loud while doing leetcode interviews or to ask friends/go to services to help practice interviewing.

Which websites/books did you use and how did it help you? Would love to hear from people who secured multiple offers and passed difficult interviews.

Would also appreciate stories of people who may not have a stellar GPA or who struggled through Berkeley but still passed difficult interviews. Feel free to name companies, although i'm mainly focused on the difficulty of the interview, rather than the company who interviewed.

Finally, if you can say how many problems you did from each website/book, that would be insightful.

Here is the only plan I have:

1. Cracking Coding Interview 

2. Endless Leetcode (maybe premium)
